That advice was to be very ditrutful of the Chevalier, who did all he could to travere his Nephew, and to make him appear indicreet and unfaithful to the Countes. After that Manicamp told her that the Letter he had written to the Count de Guiche, had o tranported him with joy, that it was impoible to get it from him, but that he hould not be in pain, for that it would be as afe in his Friends hands as in the fire;


and moreover, that he had never een a Man o much in love as the Count was, and that he would certainly love her as long as he lived. But, interrupted the Countes, what is the meaning of o many Viits that your Friend makes to Madam d' Olonne? Does he go to deire her to intercede with me for him? He does not viit her at all, Madam, anwered Manicamp, that is to ay, he has been there but once or twice; but I dicover the Chivaliers Malice in what you tell me, and I am certain the Count de Guiche will know this Knavih trick to be of this nkles stamp. But, Madam, hear my Friend before you Condemn him. I am of your Opinion, aid he to him; and indeed Manicamp gueed right: For the Chevalier had told the Countes that the Count de Guiche was in love with Madam d' Olonne, that he only erved for a Pretext, and a thouand other things of that Nature, that appeared to her o likely, that though he ditruted the Chevalier in what concerned the Count de Guiche, he could not forbear giving Credit to him in this Encounter. The next day a Lady of her Acquaintance being come to pres her to go into the Country, he let herelf be perwaded: And really fancying the Count de Guiche fale, he would not come to any


Explication with him; and not to break off all, he thought it convenient to prepoes Guitand by a fale Confidence, for fear he hould learn by other means the truth of all; Wherefore he ent him a Copy of the Count de Guiche's lat Letter, and after that her Friend and he went out of Town. The Chevalier, who had an Eye upon all the Countees Actions, and had bribed all her Servants, had the Pacquet he ent to Guitand two hours after it was made up. He took a Copy of the Count de Guiche's Letter, and cat the Pacquet into the Fire. Two days after, having learnt that the Countes was gone, he wrote to her this Letter.

                  Gapard d' Coligny, and ince Duke of Chatillon, after the Death of the Marhal his Father, and of his eldet Brother, fell in Love with Mademoielle de Bouteville;


and being the Prince of Condé fell likewie in love with her, Coligny deired him to break off his Amour, ince his Highnees deign was only Gallantry, and he intended Marriage. The Prince being Coligny's Relation and Friend, could not civilly refue him his demand; and as his Paion was of a very freh date, he did not find it difficult to get rid of it: He not only promied Coligny that he would think of her no more, but that he would erve him in this Affair againt the Marhal his Father, and his Relations who oppoed it; and indeed notwithtanding all the Orders of Parliament, and all the Obtacles that the Marhal his Father was able to raie againt it, the Prince aited Coligny o well, then of that Name, but ince the death of his Father called Chastillon, that he made him carry away Mademoielle de Bouteville, and lent him Twenty thouand Francks for his Maintenance. Coligny carried his Mitres to Chateau-Thierry, where he Conummated the marriage: From thence they proceeded farther, and went to Steny, a Town of Safety, which the Prince, whom it belonged to, had given them, for their abode. Whether that Coligny did not find his Mitres o full of Charms as he had fancied in her, or that


Love being atisfied, he had time to reflect on the ill Condition his Fortune was in, or that he feared he had given his Wife the Dieae he had, he fell into a terrible Melancholy on the Morrow after his Marriage: And while he was at Steny, his Melancholy continued upon him to that degree, that he was as contant to the Woods as a Savage. Two or three days after he went to the Army, and his Wife into a Convent of the Religieues, two Leagues from Paris. It was thither that Roquelaure, knowing the Neceity he was in, ent her a Thouand broad Pieces, and Vinevil two thouand Crowns, which Sums are till owing to them, tho the Dutches is very rich, and that Money was employed to her own ue.

The Duke of Chatillon, whom the knowledge of his Wife's humour obliged to oberve her, aw omething of an Intrigue between the Duke of Nemours and her; Glory more than Love made him receive this dicovery with an extreame Impatience. He poke of it to one of his bet Friends, who haring his grief as deeply as poible, went and told the Dutches of it. The


                  ervice that I have devoted, aid he, to the Family of his Grace your Husband, obliges me to come and give you an advice which is of Conequence. Beautyfull as you are, Madam, it is impoible but that you mut have adorers, and as certainly your intentions being good, you have not o trict a raine over your own actions; mot Women who envy you, and Men jealous of the Glory of the Duke your Husband, give an ill interpretation to all you do. My Lord your Husband, himelf has perceived that your Conduct, which tho it were more imprudent than Criminal, does not faile however to do you an injury in the World, and trouble him: you know how haughty he is, Madam, and how much he would fear to be ridiculed upon that point: I give you notice of it, and humbly beeech you to take care; for if by relying too much upon the clearnes of your Concience, you hould be too negligent of your Reputation, his Grace may come to uch Violences againt you, as would not leave you in a Condition to make appear to him your innocence. What you tell me, Sir, anwered Madam de Chatillon, ought not to urprize me; my Lord Duke began betimes to accustom me to his Caprichio's: On the day after our Wedding, he fell into o furious a jealouy of Roquelaure, who had helped him to carry me away, that he could not conceal it;


                  and yet he could never have had les reaon than at what he gave him; and now again I find that he renews his upicions, and yet I cannot devine of whom it is: All that I can ay is, that I doubt whether his mind would be at ret, tho I were in the Countrey and aw none but my Dometicks. I hall not come to further particulars with you, Madam. I even know not whether my Lord Duke aimes at any one, when he tells me he is atisfied with you; but you may upon what I have told you take meaures for your Conduct. And thereupon having taken leave of her, he left her under terrible diquiets. She immediately gave notice of all this to the Duke of Nemours, and they reolved together that they would contrain themelves more than they had thitherto done.
